---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ProductCard from '../../components/ProductCard.astro';
import products from '../../../data/products.json';

const solo = products.find(p => p.id === 'focusrite-scarlett-solo-4th-gen')!;
const at2020 = products.find(p => p.id === 'audio-technica-at2020')!;
const sony = products.find(p => p.id === 'sony-mdr-7506')!;
---

<Layout
  title="How to Set Up a Home Recording Studio on a Budget (2026) — HomeRecordingGear"
  description="How to set up a home recording studio without wasting money. A practical guide for beginners spending $100–$300."
>
  <article class="space-y-8">
    <header class="space-y-3">
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wide font-medium">Guide</p>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">How to Set Up a Home Recording Studio on a Budget</h1>
      <p class="text-gray-600 text-lg">
        You don't need a soundproofed room or $3,000 in gear. Here's the minimum viable home studio
        that actually produces quality recordings.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Step 1: Pick your microphone</h2>
      <p>
        The mic is the most important decision. Everything else you can upgrade later without it
        affecting everything else. Your mic determines what kind of interface you need
        (XLR vs USB) and how sensitive your setup is to room noise.
      </p>
      <p>
        For most beginners: <a href="/best/microphones-under-100" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">
        pick from this list</a>. Don't spend more than $150 on a mic until you've outgrown a cheaper one.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Step 2: Get an audio interface (if using XLR)</h2>
      <p>
        XLR mics need an interface. USB mics don't. If you went USB, skip this step.
        If you went XLR, the <strong>Focusrite Scarlett Solo</strong> is the standard recommendation
        at this price range — clean preamp, reliable drivers, good software bundle.
      </p>
      <ProductCard
        name={solo.name}
        price={solo.price}
        rating={solo.rating}
        reviewCount={solo.review_count}
        affiliateUrl={solo.affiliate_url}
      />
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Step 3: Get studio headphones</h2>
      <p>
        Don't use consumer headphones (AirPods, Beats) for recording or mixing — their boosted
        bass makes your mixes sound good in your ears but bad on everything else. You need flat,
        accurate headphones.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Sony MDR-7506 is the most widely used reference headphone in recording studios and
        broadcast at this price. It's not flashy, but it's right.
      </p>
      <ProductCard
        name={sony.name}
        price={sony.price}
        rating={sony.rating}
        reviewCount={sony.review_count}
        affiliateUrl={sony.affiliate_url}
      />
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Step 4: Get your recording software (DAW)</h2>
      <p>
        Every Focusrite Scarlett comes bundled with <strong>Ableton Live Lite</strong> — free,
        and good enough to get started. GarageBand is free on Mac and fully capable for basic recording.
        Logic Pro ($199) is a one-time purchase and the most common professional choice on Mac.
        Reaper is $60 and the best value paid DAW on any platform.
      </p>
      <p>Start with what's free. You'll know when you've outgrown it.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Step 5: Treat your room (for free)</h2>
      <p>
        You don't need acoustic foam panels. Before spending money on treatment, try recording
        in a closet full of clothes — the fabric absorbs reflections and it's surprisingly effective.
        Record away from hard parallel walls. Put a blanket behind your mic to kill reflections.
      </p>
      <p>
        Acoustic treatment makes a bigger difference than a more expensive mic. A $100 mic in a
        treated space sounds better than a $400 mic in a live room.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">The full budget breakdown</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
              <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-gray-700">Item</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700">Cost</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="text-gray-700">
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
              <td class="py-2 pr-4">Audio-Technica AT2020 (mic)</td>
              <td class="py-2">$99</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
              <td class="py-2 pr-4">Focusrite Scarlett Solo (interface)</td>
              <td class="py-2">$120</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
              <td class="py-2 pr-4">Sony MDR-7506 (headphones)</td>
              <td class="py-2">$100</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
              <td class="py-2 pr-4">XLR cable</td>
              <td class="py-2">$10</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
              <td class="py-2 pr-4">Mic stand</td>
              <td class="py-2">$20</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="font-semibold">
              <td class="py-2 pr-4">Total</td>
              <td class="py-2">~$349</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2">
        Prices are approximate. See <a href="/best/home-recording-bundles-under-200" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">budget bundles under $200</a> if you need to spend less.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
